.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
Adds or updates the policy that is specified as the IAM role\(aqs permissions boundary. You can use an AWS managed policy or a customer managed policy to set the boundary for a role. Use the boundary to control the maximum permissions that the role can have. Setting a permissions boundary is an advanced feature that can affect the permissions for the role.
.sp
You cannot set the boundary for a service\-linked role.
.sp
\fBWARNING:\fP
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
Policies used as permissions boundaries do not provide permissions. You must also attach a permissions policy to the role. To learn how the effective permissions for a role are evaluated, see \fI\%IAM JSON policy evaluation logic\fP in the IAM User Guide.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
See also: AWS API Documentation
.sp
See \(aqaws help\(aq for descriptions of global parameters.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
  put\-role\-permissions\-boundary
\-\-role\-name <value>
\-\-permissions\-boundary <value>
[\-\-cli\-input\-json | \-\-cli\-input\-yaml]
[\-\-generate\-cli\-skeleton <value>]
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SH OPTIONS
.sp
\fB\-\-role\-name\fP (string)
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
The name (friendly name, not ARN) of the IAM role for which you want to set the permissions boundary.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fB\-\-permissions\-boundary\fP (string)
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
The ARN of the policy that is used to set the permissions boundary for the role.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fB\-\-cli\-input\-json\fP | \fB\-\-cli\-input\-yaml\fP (string)
Reads arguments from the JSON string provided. The JSON string follows the format provided by \fB\-\-generate\-cli\-skeleton\fP\&. If other arguments are provided on the command line, those values will override the JSON\-provided values. It is not possible to pass arbitrary binary values using a JSON\-provided value as the string will be taken literally. This may not be specified along with \fB\-\-cli\-input\-yaml\fP\&.
.sp
\fB\-\-generate\-cli\-skeleton\fP (string)
Prints a JSON skeleton to standard output without sending an API request. If provided with no value or the value \fBinput\fP, prints a sample input JSON that can be used as an argument for \fB\-\-cli\-input\-json\fP\&. Similarly, if provided \fByaml\-input\fP it will print a sample input YAML that can be used with \fB\-\-cli\-input\-yaml\fP\&. If provided with the value \fBoutput\fP, it validates the command inputs and returns a sample output JSON for that command.
.sp
See \(aqaws help\(aq for descriptions of global parameters.
.SH EXAMPLES
.sp
\fBTo apply a permissions boundary based on a custom policy to an IAM role\fP
.sp
The following \fBput\-role\-permissions\-boundary\fP example applies the custom policy named \fBintern\-boundary\fP as the permissions boundary for the specified IAM role.
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
aws iam put\-role\-permissions\-boundary \e
    \-\-permissions\-boundary arn:aws:iam::123456789012:policy/intern\-boundary \e
    \-\-role\-name lambda\-application\-role
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
This command produces no output.
.sp
\fBTo apply a permissions boundary based on an AWS managed policy to an IAM role\fP
.sp
The following \fBput\-role\-permissions\-boundary\fP example applies the AWS managed \fBPowerUserAccess\fP policy as the permissions boundary for the specified IAM role .
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.nf
.ft C
aws iam put\-role\-permissions\-boundary \e
    \-\-permissions\-boundary arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/PowerUserAccess \e
    \-\-role\-name x\-account\-admin
.ft P
.fi
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
This command produces no output.
